An Aetna InteliHealth/Harvard Medical School Look At The News --
Obesity In Middle Age Cuts Years Off Life

 PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- People who are overweight at 40 are likely
to die at least three years sooner than those who are slim,
meaning that in terms of life expectancy, being fat during middle
age is just as bad as smoking, researchers say.  Read the story
and comments from a Harvard physician.

http://www.intelihealth.com/IH/ihtIH/EMIHC000/333/333/359838.html
_


Japan's Emperor To Have Prostate Surgery

TOKYO (AP) -- Emperor Akihito will undergo an operation for
prostate cancer on Jan.  18 at a Tokyo hospital, a spokesman for
the Imperial Palace said Wednesday.

http://www.intelihealth.com/IH/ihtIH/EMIHC000/333/333/359888.html
_


Obesity Cuts Life Span For Young Adults

CHICAGO (AP) -- Being obese at age 20 can cut up to 20 years off
a person's life, with the biggest impact on black men, according
to yet another study that underscores the long-term dangers of
being overweight.

http://www.intelihealth.com/IH/ihtIH/EMIHC000/333/333/359858.html
_


